
I already knew the answer, and maybe it wasn’t socially acceptable to ask someone something like this, especially when their orientation was fairly ambiguous, but his vulnerability had a magnetic pulse. She did something to him that shattered the façade he maintained all day, and all she had to do was occupy his thoughts. He talked about her as if he was crafting a sculpture, with tender fingers and attentive eyes.
Yet, when he peered at me over his shoulder, I was stricken by the return of his wooden exterior, the tightness around his eyes, and the seconds it took before he could push out the words, “No. I don’t.”


